  "summary": "Resolution is the Argus/Green Markets Tampa molten sulphur QUARTERLY contract for Q3 2026 (the \"World Bank liquid sulphur\" label is a misnomer \u2014 WB Pink Sheet has no sulphur series). The contract trajectory: Q4'25 $310 \u2192 Q1'26 $379 \u2192 Q2'26 ~$540/lt. Q3'26 was unsettled at question open but will be known by the Aug 1 resolution. The Strait of Hormuz crisis drove a massive June surge (ADNOC $860 fob record, CFR China $1075, Mosaic >$1200) with producers pushing Q3 toward spot. Countervailing: the Tampa contract is a negotiated buyer-supplier settlement that historically comes in below spot chatter (Q1'26 chatter $475-520 vs $379 settled), and Hormuz de-escalation is a downside risk. A scenario mixture (base ~$810 / downside ~$650 / upside ~$980, with long-ton\u2192metric-ton conversion) centers at ~$787/metric ton with P10-P90 of ~$613-997. Both bounds open.",
  "reasoning": "Forecast submitted.\n\n**Summary:** This question resolves on the **Argus/Green Markets Tampa molten sulphur quarterly contract for Q3 2026** (the \"World Bank\" label is a misnomer \u2014 the WB Pink Sheet has no sulphur series).\n\n**Key findings:**\n- Contract trajectory: Q4'25 $310 \u2192 Q1'26 $379 \u2192 Q2'26 ~$540/lt. Q3'26 was **unsettled** at question open but will be known by the Aug 1 resolution.\n- The Strait of Hormuz crisis drove a major June surge (ADNOC $860/t fob record, CFR China $1075, Mosaic citing >$1200), with producers pushing Q3 toward spot.\n- Countervailing: the Tampa contract is a negotiated buyer-supplier settlement that historically comes in **below** spot chatter (Q1'26 chatter was $475-520 vs $379 settled), and Hormuz de-escalation is a downside risk.\n\n**Distribution** (USD/metric ton, both bounds open): centered ~**$785**, with P10\u2013P90 of ~**$613\u2013995**, built from a scenario mixture (base $810 / downside $650 / upside $980) including the long-ton\u2192metric-ton conversion.",
